AGI - The Ukrainian conflict - which "have not lasted for three years, but since 11" with the war in Donbass and the Russian annexation of Crimea - has arrived at a "turn", whose direction is still difficult to predict >, but which is certainly marked by the deep fracture consumed between Kiev and its main ally, Washington. That 2025 would open a new chapter > was quite clear to those who, like Simone Attilio Bellezza, dedicated his life to Ukrainian studies and post-Soviet area.
Professor of Contemporary History at the University of Eastern Piedmont, Bellezza is co-curator of the volume released for Scholé "The Ukrainian War of Independence. > As the conflict has changed the country (2014-2024)”>, ten years in which war confrontation has profoundly influenced and transformed society, culture and Ukrainian politics. The volume reflects on these changes with the essays of 12 Italian and Ukrainian scholars who aim to interpret the war in the medium-long period to try to understand what the future of Ukraine will be.
The major changes that occurred in this period, explains in an interview with AGI the same Beauty, “are basically three: a greater “ucrainization” of the Country >, with the populations that mixed up because of the internal emigration driven by war”. This, the scholar continues, “has allowed to create a more cohesive nation > that is known more and that this time speaks a single language, the Ukrainian, while the Russian is perceived as the language of the invader”. &nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
The other great transformation is that of a “democratization” of the country, with a “progressive marginalization of oligarchs from power and the affirmation of the primacy of politics”. On the subject of rights, it points out Beauty, just remember that “the Istanbul Convention on Gender Rights was approved during the war at first reading by the Ukrainian Parliament”; It was a step claimed as “an ideological choice to belong to a world other than Putin’s, that is, Western democracies.”
Finally, it is daily life that has changed a lot:> “Violence and destruction are widespread, Ukraine is a country where almost everyone has had a family victim, curfew, bombs, restrictions on energy supplies.” Today, the Ukrainian report to President Volodymyr Zelensky also changed: it suffered a decline in popularity, but to say that its consent is 4%, as U.S. President Donald Trump recently did, it seems an attempt to “delegitimate” it along with the appeals to indirect new elections, declares the teacher.
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Zelensky's mandate has expired last year, but “it should not be forgotten that he is the only legitimate president and this is also known by the Ukrainians”, explains Bellezza, “because the Constitution provides that in case of war you can not go to the urns”. Reporting recent polls, which give Zelensky to 57%, the expert admits that the Ukrainian leader "has alienated part of popular consensus for several reasons, including some choices in the management of conflict and government officials more tied to his circle of collaborators, than a logic of competence".
“But this time the United States faces,” continues Beauty, “it is doing nothing but reuniting the nation around the president again: Ukrainians feel betrayed by the United States and the West, by those who were the first their allies and who from one moment to another have married Putin's thesis." Now Zelensky's future depends on how he can close this international game > on a possible truce, says Beauty, according to which "it is not obvious that you can really get to a truce, because I think Zelensky has the possibility, in case it is supported by a strong popular consensus, not to accept a truce that is a complete surrender".
The red line on which Kiev will not yield are guarantees of security, more than territorial integrity: "How can Russia prevent a new attack on Ukraine > perhaps in a year or two, when it has already established that it will not be part of NATO?" The most important thing "would be able to bind Ukraine to NATO's security system, always that it continues to exist" under Trump's edges.
